When you create a model version or open a model, Einstein shows you a list of insights, starting with the most statistically significant ones. These descriptive insights help you explore factors that contribute to the outcome.

Select any variable from the Variables panel to focus your exploration and delve deeper into insights. Begin with variables showing higher correlations to the outcome.

Note: Correlation is not causation. It describes the strength of association between variables, not whether they causally affect each other.

Open a Model. Select a variable you want to investigate in the Variables panel. The insights list shows insights associated with the selected variable only.

Scroll through the list and examine any insights that interest you.

When selecting a numeric explanatory variable, Einstein displays a bar chart with the numeric variable along the horizontal axis.

When selecting a text (categorical) variable, Einstein displays a bar chart with the text variable along the horizontal axis.

When selecting a date variable, Einstein displays a chart with the date variable along the horizontal axis.

A second-order insight shows how the combination of two explanatory variables explains variation in the outcome variable. The combined impact of both variables together on the outcome is called the interaction effect.
